"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of German <b>Reither</b>, a variant of   Reiter  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Reiter","meanings":["German:","occupational name for a mounted soldier or knight, from Middle Low German <i>rider</i>, Middle High German <i>rīter</i> ‘rider’. It is also found in some central European countries, e.g. in Czechia and Slovenia. Compare   Raiter  .","variant of   Reuter   1."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Ryther I was born about 1350, in Yorkshire, England as the son of Robert Ryther and Lady Margaret Southeby. He married Dame Sibyl Aldeburgh about 1384, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He lived in Hare